      =C2=A0Programming note: Money Stuff will be off tomorrow, back on Mon=
day.ESL ESGI  wrote the other day about how JPMorgan Chase & Co. got in som=
e hot water for agreeing to finance the European Super League, the now appa=
rently dead proposal to start a lucrative new league for the biggest Europe=
an soccer clubs. As the financier of this plan, JPMorgan came in for a lot =
of abuse on Twitter from European soccer fans. =E2=80=9CAccount is now clos=
ed and this =C2=A332.25 is going elsewhere,=E2=80=9D tweeted one former Cha=
se customer.I thought this was funny, and I drew what I thought was a somew=
hat overwrought and tongue-in-cheek=C2=A0comparison between the Super Leagu=
e and other sorts of social responsibility decisions that banks make. My po=
int, I suppose, was that =E2=80=9Cis this bad for sports?=E2=80=9D is not r=
eally on the list of social responsibility and=C2=A0sustainability question=
s that banks generally ask when they consider new business. =E2=80=9CIs it =
bad for the environment,=E2=80=9D sure, =E2=80=9Cis it=C2=A0good for divers=
ity,=E2=80=9D sure; there is a longish list of topics that everyone underst=
ands are important for social responsibility, and new topics periodically g=
et added to that list through various forms of activism. But =E2=80=9Cis it=
 good for soccer fans=E2=80=9D seemed, to me, to be rather a different sort=
 of topic, one that would be a little silly to add to the list.Nope, totall=
y wrong, it=E2=80=99s life-and-death stuff:A sustainability rating agency h=
as downgraded JP Morgan Chase after the US bank was revealed to be funding =
the failed European Super League (ESL) breakaway attempt.Standard Ethics, w=
hich grades corporations on their sustainability and is modelled on credit-=
ratings agencies, criticised the clubs as well as the bank.=E2=80=9CStandar=
d Ethics judges both the orientations shown by the football clubs involved =
in the project and those of the US bank to be contrary to sustainability be=
st practices, which are defined by the agency according to UN, OECD and Eur=
opean Union guidelines, and take into account the interests of the stakehol=
ders,=E2=80=9D it said.It downgraded JP Morgan from an =E2=80=9Cadequate=E2=
=80=9D rating to =E2=80=9Cnon-compliant=E2=80=9D in light of the ESL. Stand=
ard Ethics charges a fee to some companies to rate them based on environmen=
tal, social and governance performance, although JP Morgan=E2=80=99s rating=
 was unsolicited.Every public-company chief executive officer  loves to tal=
k about =E2=80=9Ctaking into account the interests of stakeholders,=E2=80=
=9D not least JPMorgan CEO Jamie Dimon. In 2019, the Business Roundtable, a=
 group of public-company CEOs=C2=A0led by Dimon, concluded that =E2=80=9Cth=
e purpose of a corporation=E2=80=9D had changed and now it had to take into=
 account =E2=80=9Call stakeholders.=E2=80=9D When I made fun of the Busines=
s Roundtable statement, I put a picture of Dimon at the top of my column. H=
e=E2=80=99s a stakeholdery guy. It=E2=80=99s just that it apparently never =
occurred to him that sports fans are stakeholders in the relevant sense.=C2=
=A0Or here is =E2=80=9CJPMorgan Gets Caught Up in Europe=E2=80=99s Big Socc=
er League Blunder,=E2=80=9D from Bloomberg News:The size of the proposed fi=
nancing meant the bank stood to receive millions of dollars in fees. Instea=
d, the project appears doomed after most of the teams pulled out with fans,=
 players and politicians decrying the plan. JPMorgan is now left to assess =
the fallout from a proposal that appears to have underestimated the potenti=
al backlash from upending a sport with deep traditions and local roots.=E2=
=80=9CIt didn=E2=80=99t seem co-ordinated and almost didn=E2=80=99t seem th=
ought through,=E2=80=9D said Steve Greenfield, a professor of sports law at=
 the University of Westminster. =E2=80=9CIt was business-based and lost sig=
ht of the sporting connotations.=E2=80=9DYes! Right! Look: I am sure that a=
t least a few members of the JPMorgan deal team, or of the committees that =
approved the transaction, were European soccer fans. Like most=C2=A0soccer =
fans, I would guess, they probably believe in the importance of the pyramid=
al structure of club competitions; they think that the rigors and uncertain=
ty of qualification for the Champions League, and of promotion and relegati=
on in domestic leagues, make for better games and a more interesting and me=
aningful sport. Probably some of them worked diligently on this financing, =
and then went home to complain to their spouses that they were ruining the =
game of soccer. Probably some of them made those complaints to each other, =
at the office, while working on the financing.But they put those personal f=
eelings aside because they work at a bank, and their job is to do big deals=
 and earn big fees. They were =E2=80=9Cbusiness-based and lost sight of the=
 sporting connotations=E2=80=9D because they assumed that their job, at wor=
k, was to do business, and that the sporting connotations were a set of per=
sonal aesthetic preferences that had no legitimate place at their work. If =
your boss called you in=C2=A0and said =E2=80=9Cwe need you to work on this =
European Super League financing=E2=80=9D and you replied =E2=80=9CI=C2=A0ca=
n=E2=80=99t do that, I=E2=80=99m a Leicester fan,=E2=80=9D you would be =E2=
=80=A6=C2=A0fired? Like that is just not a thing you can say! You can=E2=80=
=99t be like =E2=80=9CI am sorry but the sporting connotations just take pr=
ecedence over the business, for me.=E2=80=9DOr, I mean, that=E2=80=99s how =
I and probably every single investment banker understood the situation as o=
f last week. Right now, being bad for sports seems to be going badly for JP=
Morgan, and for all I know now there=C2=A0is=C2=A0a norm of social responsi=
bility that your deals can=E2=80=99t make sports less sporting. =E2=80=9CI=
=E2=80=99m sorry boss but I think this deal would be bad for the game of so=
ccer=E2=80=9D is now a totally reasonable thing for an investment banker to=
 say, something really that a banker would be=C2=A0obligated=C2=A0to say, a=
nd to escalate to the highest levels. Banks have a responsibility to the ga=
me of soccer, it turns out.ArchegosThe interesting thing about  Archegos Ca=
pital Management is that it made very levered bets on a handful of stocks, =
and then those stocks went up a whole lot over a fairly short period of tim=
e. Then they went down a whole lot, sure, wiping out Archegos and causing b=
illions of dollars of losses for some of the banks that financed Archegos=
=E2=80=99s positions. But first they went up.=C2=A0One reason this matters =
is that, when Archegos first put on these positions, they were relatively s=
mall. Then they became big, by virtue of going up. Archegos made very lever=
ed bets, and the bets kept winning, and Archegos kept plowing its winnings =
into bigger levered bets. By the time it blew up =E2=80=94=C2=A0or by, like=
, a few days before it blew up =E2=80=94=C2=A0Archegos was a very large cli=
ent of the banks who were financing its positions. But when it=C2=A0started=
, it wasn=E2=80=99t. I mean, it started as a family office in 2013 with $20=
0 million of assets, which is a small client as investment banks go, though=
 one with a notable pedigree. (It=E2=80=99s the family office of Bill Hwang=
, who used to run Tiger Asia, an important =E2=80=9CTiger Cub=E2=80=9D hedg=
e fund.) It grew over time into a bigger and more=C2=A0important client. Bu=
t its transformation into a $20 billion fund with something like $100 billi=
on of gross notional exposure happened within  the last year or two, throug=
h a series of large and rapidly successful bets.So on the one hand there ar=
e stories about, for instance, Goldman Sachs Group Inc. salespeople  thirst=
